{"type":"freeform","cover":{"titleText":"","subTitleText":"","presenterText":"","dateText":"","logos":[]},"section":{"sectionText":"","smallerSectionText":""},"freeform":{"content":[[{"type":"text","stretch":true,"fillArea":true,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"grey","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":false,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"span":4,"markdown":"The number of malaria-positive cases dropped sharply in mid-2024, with volumes ~25–32% below expected in March–April and remaining depressed through much of the year. By 2025, detected cases rose again, returning closer to expected levels by June (~2% below trend).

ACT treatment closely followed the trend in positive cases, with marked declines in 2024 and higher volumes in 2025. By June 2025, treatment levels remained somewhat close to expected, and the close alignment with positive cases indicates that most detected cases continued to be treated.

Malaria typically rises during the rainy season, but timing and peak sharpness vary by district. The model captures seasonality at the national level, but does not fully reflect these local differences."},{"type":"figure","stretch":true,"fillArea":false,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"none","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":true,"figureAdditionalScale":0.8,"presentationObjectInReportInfo":{"id":"891479dd-025e-4c32-b6bb-3da497bba932","moduleId":"m003","selectedReplicantValue":"","isDefault":false}}]],"useHeader":true,"headerText":"Measles Vaccination"}}

{"type":"freeform","cover":{"titleText":"","subTitleText":"","presenterText":"","dateText":"","logos":[]},"section":{"sectionText":"","smallerSectionText":""},"freeform":{"content":[[{"type":"text","span":3,"markdown":"ANC1 volumes trended upward from late 2024, peaking around March–May 2025 near 29,000 visits, and then stabilizing just below 28,000.

ANC4 showed slower but steady growth, reaching about 20,000 visits by mid-2025 — consistently ~8–9k lower than ANC1, indicating incomplete progression through visits.

Addressing gaps between first and fourth visits remains critical to ensure continuity of care and improved antenatal outcomes.","stretch":true,"fillArea":true,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"grey","placeholderInvisible":false,"placeholderStretch":true,"placeholderHeight":50,"useFigureAdditionalScale":false,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"imgHeight":300,"imgFit":"inside","imgStretch":true,"hideFigureCaption":false,"hideFigureSubCaption":false,"hideFigureFootnote":false},{"type":"figure","presentationObjectInReportInfo":{"id":"3fbf5da0-7fde-432d-b6e7-8dde07448f21","moduleId":"m003","isDefault":false,"selectedReplicantValue":""},"stretch":true,"fillArea":false,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"none","placeholderInvisible":false,"placeholderStretch":true,"placeholderHeight":50,"useFigureAdditionalScale":true,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"imgHeight":300,"imgFit":"inside","imgStretch":true,"hideFigureCaption":false,"hideFigureSubCaption":false,"hideFigureFootnote":false}]],"useHeader":true,"headerText":"Trends in antenatal care","useFooter":false,"footerText":""}}

{"type":"freeform","cover":{"titleText":"","subTitleText":"","presenterText":"","dateText":"","logos":[]},"section":{"sectionText":"","smallerSectionText":""},"freeform":{"content":[[{"type":"text","stretch":true,"fillArea":true,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"grey","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":false,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"span":4,"markdown":"ANC1 visits were consistently above expectations in 2025, averaging ~26,900 per month vs. ~24,200 expected (~11% higher), with June 2025 ~26,200 visits (~9% above expected).

ANC4 visits stayed close to expected levels, averaging ~19,300 per month vs. ~18,800 expected (~3% higher), with June 2025 ~18,900 visits (~5% above expected).

Both indicators align with expected trends, though ANC1 shows clearer gains. Continuity remains a concern, as fewer women complete ANC4 compared to ANC1."},{"type":"figure","stretch":true,"fillArea":false,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"none","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":true,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"presentationObjectInReportInfo":{"id":"c8b175ca-cf5e-41d9-a049-09ee5ba851d2","moduleId":"m003","selectedReplicantValue":"","isDefault":false}}]],"useHeader":true,"headerText":"ANC1 shows slight surpluses in 2025, while ANC4 stays near trend, but continuity gap remains"}}

{"type":"freeform","cover":{"titleText":"","subTitleText":"","presenterText":"","dateText":"","logos":[]},"section":{"sectionText":"","smallerSectionText":""},"freeform":{"content":[[{"type":"text","stretch":true,"fillArea":true,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"grey","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":false,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"span":4,"markdown":"In 2025, deliveries rose steadily above expected levels, reaching ~14% higher than trend by June. This shows stronger uptake of facility-based births — a key entry point for maternal–newborn care.

Newborn PNC visits rose to ~8% above expected by June 2025, but gains are smaller than for deliveries. While gains are smaller than for deliveries, volumes still reached about 90% of delivery levels, suggesting some newborns are not receiving timely follow-up after birth.

Maternal PNC visits climbed to ~9% above expected by June 2025. PNC for mothers reached about 93% of delivery levels, pointing to modest but persistent gaps in linking facility births with postpartum care."},{"type":"figure","stretch":true,"fillArea":false,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"none","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":true,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"presentationObjectInReportInfo":{"id":"42d3fcf1-a5a9-4078-9ffa-d9522b99a42b","moduleId":"m003","selectedReplicantValue":"","isDefault":false}}]],"useHeader":true,"headerText":"Institutional deliveries and PNC visits rise above expected levels in 2025, but continuity of care gap remains"}}

{"type":"freeform","cover":{"titleText":"","subTitleText":"","presenterText":"","dateText":"","logos":[]},"section":{"sectionText":"","smallerSectionText":""},"freeform":{"content":[[{"type":"text","stretch":true,"fillArea":true,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"grey","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":false,"figureAdditionalScale":1,"span":4,"markdown":"The number of malaria-positive cases dropped sharply in mid-2024, with volumes ~25–32% below expected in March–April and remaining depressed through much of the year. By 2025, detected cases rose again, returning closer to expected levels by June (~2% below trend).

ACT treatment closely followed the trend in positive cases, with marked declines in 2024 and higher volumes in 2025. By June 2025, treatment levels remained somewhat close to expected, and the close alignment with positive cases indicates that most detected cases continued to be treated.

Malaria typically rises during the rainy season, but timing and peak sharpness vary by district. The model captures seasonality at the national level, but does not fully reflect these local differences."},{"type":"figure","stretch":true,"fillArea":false,"textSize":1,"textBackground":"none","placeholderInvisible":false,"useFigureAdditionalScale":true,"figureAdditionalScale":0.8,"presentationObjectInReportInfo":{"id":"891479dd-025e-4c32-b6bb-3da497bba932","moduleId":"m003","selectedReplicantValue":"","isDefault":false}}]],"useHeader":true,"headerText":"Measles Vaccination"}}
